## 2. Architecture & Design Decisions

### Database Strategy

- **Dual Database Approach**: SQLite for mobile (better performance), IndexedDB for web (browser compatibility)
- **Automatic Fallback**: If SQLite fails, automatically falls back to IndexedDB
- **Data Encryption**: All sensitive data encrypted using CryptoJS with configurable keys
- **Migration Support**: Schema versioning with automatic data migration

### Form Architecture

- **Reactive Forms**: Angular reactive forms with comprehensive validation
- **Section-Based**: 10 distinct sections for better UX and maintainability
- **Custom Controls**: ControlValueAccessor implementation for reusable form components
- **Accordion UI**: Collapsible sections for better mobile experience

### Sync Strategy

- **Offline-Only by Default**: No internet required; sync occurs over local LAN/mesh to a camp-server on Raspberry Pi
- **LAN Provisioning via QR**: Staff generates QR with multiple `serverUrls` + short-lived sync token; device tries each URL until one works, then syncs
- **Queue-Based**: Changes queued locally, synced in batches
- **USB Fallback**: Encrypted export/import bundles for offline transfer via USB when networking is unavailable
- **Conflict Resolution**: Timestamp-based conflict detection
- **Auto-Sync**: Automatic sync every 5 minutes with manual trigger option

### Security Considerations

- **Data Encryption**: Local data encrypted before storage; USB bundles encrypted and integrity-checked
- **Input Validation**: Comprehensive client-side validation with server-side backup on camp-server
- **File Upload Security**: File type and size validation
- **Authentication**: JWT-based auth for staff; short-lived sync-only tokens for guest device sync in camps (no internet required)

## 3. Development Rules & Best Practices

### 3a. Keep Tests Updated

**Always** update the relevant test files and components after changing logic:

- Update `/db-test` component when modifying database operations
- Update `/data-viewer` component when changing data structures
- Test QR functionality through `/qr-test` page after QR service changes
- Use the built-in testing components to verify changes work correctly
- This ensures we can reliably test changes locally and catch regressions

### 3b. Scope of Changes

**Do not** modify existing code that is unrelated to the specific user request without asking for permission first.

- Focus on the specific feature or bug being addressed
- If you spot an opportunity for a refactor or improvement outside the current task, please suggest it first rather than just implementing it
- Maintain backward compatibility with existing data and functionality
- Document any side effects or dependencies when making changes

### 3c. Code Style & Consistency

When adding new functionality, please follow the existing code style and patterns:

- Look at existing form section components (e.g., `BasicInfoComponent`, `MemberInfoComponent`) as templates
- Follow the established service patterns (e.g., `DatabaseService`, `SyncService`)
- Use the same validation patterns and error handling approaches
- Maintain the same file organization and naming conventions
- If you believe a different pattern or approach is better, please propose it and explain the benefits _before_ implementing

### 3d. Code Organization

**Follow the established Angular/Ionic patterns:**

- Components in `src/app/components/` organized by feature
- Services in `src/app/services/` with clear single responsibilities
- Interfaces in `src/app/interfaces/` for type safety
- Pages in `src/app/pages/` for routable components

### 3e. Database Operations

**Always use the database service abstraction:**

- Never directly access SQLite or IndexedDB in components
- Use `DatabaseService` for all database operations
- Handle both success and error cases
- Queue changes through `SyncQueueService` for offline support

### 3f. Form Development

**Follow the established form patterns:**

- Use reactive forms with proper validation
- Implement ControlValueAccessor for reusable form sections
- Include proper error handling and user feedback
- Maintain consistent validation messages in Afrikaans

### 3g. Mobile Considerations

**Always test on mobile devices:**

- Use Ionic components for native feel
- Test camera and file system permissions
- Verify offline functionality
- Check performance on lower-end devices

### 3h. Type Safety

**Maintain strict TypeScript usage:**

- Use interfaces for all data structures
- Avoid `any` type except when absolutely necessary
- Implement proper error handling with typed exceptions
- Use Angular's dependency injection properly

### 3i. Language Consistency

**Maintain Afrikaans language throughout:**

- All user-facing text in Afrikaans
- Consistent terminology usage
- Proper Afrikaans form validation messages
- Comments in English, UI in Afrikaans

## 4. File Structure & Naming Conventions

### Component Structure

```
src/app/components/
├── sections/           # Form sections
│   ├── basic-info/
│   ├── member-info/
│   └── ...
├── shared/            # Reusable components
│   ├── header/
│   ├── theme-toggle/
│   └── ...
└── features/          # Feature-specific components
    ├── qr-scanner/
    ├── data-viewer/
    └── ...
```

### Service Organization

- `database.service.ts` - Database abstraction layer
- `sync.service.ts` - Synchronization logic
- `api.service.ts` - HTTP client wrapper
- `export.service.ts` - Data export functionality
- `qr.service.ts` - QR code generation/scanning

### Interface Definitions

- All interfaces in `src/app/interfaces/`
- Use descriptive names matching form sections
- Maintain consistency with database schema

## 5. Testing & Debugging Guidelines

### 5a. Database Testing

**Use the built-in test components:**

- `/db-test` route for database connection testing
- `/data-viewer` route for data inspection
- Monitor sync status through UI components

### 5b. Form Testing

**Test all validation scenarios:**

- Required field validation
- Format validation (ID numbers, phone numbers, emails)
- Age/date consistency validation
- File upload validation

### 5c. Cross-Platform Testing

**Test on all target platforms:**

- Web browser (Chrome, Firefox, Safari)
- Android device/emulator
- iOS device/simulator (when available)

### 5d. Offline Testing

**Verify offline functionality:**

- Disable network and test form submission
- Verify data persistence across app restarts
- Test sync when connection restored

## 6. Deployment & Build Considerations

### Mobile Builds

- Use Capacitor for native builds
- Test on actual devices before release
- Handle platform-specific permissions properly
- Optimize bundle size for mobile networks

### Web Deployment

- Ensure IndexedDB compatibility across browsers
- Test service worker functionality
- Optimize for mobile web browsers
- Handle browser storage limitations

## 7. Security & Privacy Guidelines

### Data Protection

- Encrypt all personal information before storage
- Use secure transmission protocols for sync
- Implement proper user authentication
- Regular security audits of dependencies

### File Handling

- Validate file types and sizes
- Sanitize file names
- Secure file storage (local and cloud)
- Implement proper access controls

## 8. Collaboration & Learning Principles

### 8a. Learning-Focused Approach

**IMPORTANT**: The project owner is a junior developer and should always be treated as one. All explanations, code, and suggestions should be clear, explicit, and easy for a developer new to programming concepts to understand. The goal is not just to get the code working, but to understand _why_ it works and learn proper development practices.

### 8b. Clarify Before Acting

Before implementing a new feature or making significant changes, **always** ask clarifying questions to understand the "what" and the "why." This ensures we are aligned on the goal before diving into the "how." Never assume requirements - always confirm understanding first.

### 8c. Educational Explanations

When providing solutions or making changes:

- Explain the reasoning behind architectural decisions
- Break down complex concepts into simple, understandable parts
- Provide context for why certain patterns or approaches are used
- Reference learning resources when introducing new concepts
- Encourage questions and provide patient, detailed answers

### 8d. Mentorship Approach

Treat every interaction as a teaching opportunity:

- Point out best practices and explain why they matter
- Highlight potential pitfalls and how to avoid them
- Suggest improvements while explaining the benefits
- Encourage experimentation in a safe, guided manner
- Build confidence through positive reinforcement and constructive feedback

## 9. Collaboration & Task Management Protocol

### 9a. Implementation Process

When working on features, follow this structured approach:

- **Analysis First**: Understand requirements before coding
- **Design Review**: Discuss architecture before implementation
- **Incremental Development**: Implement in small, testable chunks
- **Testing**: Verify functionality before marking complete

### 9b. Code Review Standards

- Maintain existing code patterns and conventions
- Test all changes on multiple platforms
- Update documentation when adding new features
- Ensure backward compatibility with existing data

### 9c. Task Completion Criteria

A task is only complete when:

- Functionality works on all target platforms
- Proper error handling implemented
- User feedback/loading states added
- No breaking changes to existing features
- Code follows established patterns

### 9d. Emergency Procedures

For critical bugs or security issues:

- Document the issue immediately
- Implement minimal fix first
- Test thoroughly before deployment
- Plan proper solution for next iteration
